{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_queenofspades_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280608701/1958021101/0825.xml":{"full_text":"DAVID LAWRENCE\nWhen Will the Pickup' Come?\nInevitability of Business Recovery\nCalled More Important Than Time\n\u25a0file most fascinating game\namong businessmen\u2014and it's\na game with high stakes\u2014is\nguessing just when the \u201cpick\nup\u201d will come in the economic\nsituation of the country.\nThere's a distinct differ\nence between \u201crecovery\" and\n\u201cpickup.\" It is conceded\nthat, when the \u201cupturn\u201d\ncomes, it could be slow and\nmight precede by a good\nmany months an actual state\nof \"recovery\nWhat is meant, of course,\nis that the generalities which\nhave been heard for the last\nseveral weeks are being chal\nlenged as the first month\nand-a-half of 1958 have al\nready passed. The idea that\nbusiness will recover in the\nsecond six months\u2014a widely\nheld view\u2014presupposes a cer\ntain regularity about eco\nnomic timetables. Business\ntrends don\u2019t behave that way.\nas one factor after another\nhas to arise in an unpredict\nable sequence until the whole\npicture has changed. Nobody\ncan tell in advance when\n\u201cconfidence\u201d will come back\nand when commitments will\nbegin to be made for further\nexpenditures. But when \u201ccon\nfidence\u201d has actually been re\nstored, everyone will recognize\nits return.\nThe biggest fallacy of all\nis the widely spread argu\nment\u2014mostly by the poli\nticians that Government\nitself can give business \u201ca\nshot in the arm\u201d or that a\ntax cut will be a panacea.\nThe administration it\nself has had to deal with\nsuch predictions cautiously\nand ambiguously because it\ndoesn\u2019t want to seem to be a\nkilljoy or to be \u201cinflexible\"\nin its approach to possible\nsolutions. But the truth is\na tax cut is unlikely unless\nDORIS FLEESON\nSnafu in the Agencies Probe\nPotentially Important Inquiry on Conduct\nSeen Hurt by Pettiness and Foolishness\nNot even the Pentagon hac\nproduced a snafu equal to\nthe one in which the inquiry\ninto the Federal regulatory\nagencies is now trapped.\nIt is a situation in which\nnobody has been wise, few\nhave been brave and some\nhave been accused of be\ning corrupt, while practically\neverybody involved has been\nimpetuous and foolish.\nThe inquiry is needed and\nis potentially one of the most\nImportant ever held here. It\nbegan at a level equal to its\nhigh mission: it rests to\nnight in a slough of petty\ndissension, back-biting and,\nsordid personalities.\nThe subcommittee decided\nit did not like the methods of\nits counsel, but instead of\nfiring him immediately it\nbegan a calculated campaign\nto harass and discredit him so\nhe would resign. It has al\nlowed witnesses who were\nthemselves under fire to\nabuse him: at one point a Re\npublican member of the com\nmittee suggested counsel be\nmade to take the witness\nchair and be put under oath.\nCounsel Bernard Schwartz\nhas fought back with more\nCongress Gets Lesson\nIn Short Distances\nBy the Associated Press\nWhen scientists talk about\nshort distances they can mean\nsome so short \u201cspace and time\nmay lose their usual meaning.\u201d\nDr. Murray Gell-Mann used\nthat phrase today in tell\ning congressional investigators\nabout a new territory scientists\nare trying to explore.\nHe referred to one distance\nso short it would have to be\nmultiplied 254 million million\ntimes to equal 1 inch.\nHe called it \u201cthe realm of\nthe very small where even\nour most successful theories\nprobably break down.\u201d\nWithin such short distances,\nhe said, reactions involving the\nmost energetic types of physical\nforce take place. That is, he\nexplained, \u201cthe higher the\nenergy, the smaller the dis\ntances involved.\u201d\n\u201cHere no one knows what to\nexpect, and many physicists\nbelieve that space and time\nmay lose their usual meaning\nwhen such short intervals are\ninvolved.\u201d He didn't amplify.\nDr. Gell-Mann, a California\nInstitute of Technology re\nsearcher. appeared before a\nsubcommittee of the Senate-\nHouse Atomic Energy Commit\ntee. That group is looking into\n2 Telephones to Desk Called\nToo Many for Congress\nAn Ohio representative has\nblasted as a symbol of \u201crank\nhappy, bureaucratic Washing\nton\u201d the recent installation of\na second telephone on desks of\nmembers of Congress.\nRepresentative John E. Hen\nderson, Ohio Republican, said\nscornfully that the new tele\nphones are a \u201cgreat example of\nefficiency.\u201d He said he has had\nhis own removed.\nFormerly, Capitol Hill had a\nmanuel switchboard. Any Sen\nator or Representative could\npick up his phone and ask the\noperator to ring any other Sen\nator or House member or Capi\ntol Hill office.\nThen a new automatic switch- 1\na deep depression ensues.\nFew here really believe in\nthe concept. It could be a\ndangerous move, .too, and\ndestroy confidence in the\ndollar, especially if the Fed\neral deficit goes to $7 or $8\nbillion\u2014which it could cer\ntainly do if. in addition to\nthe expected drop in revenue\nyielding a deficit of 83 bil\nlion/ there is a $3 or $4 bil\nlion loss in receipts due to\ntax reductions.\nFor, at a time when the\nGovernment needs revenues\nto meet big budgets, the idea\nof slashing off several bil\nlions in taxes and giving the\nmoney to consumers\u2014who\nneed it very little. Judging\nby the way the consumer\nfigures are standing up\u2014is\nto ignore the basic weak\nnesses which prevail today\nin the capital goods or\nheavy-goods industries.\nThe fatal error of the\n1930 s was \u201cpump priming\u201d\non the consumer side. It\ndidn\u2019t result in the building\nof more plant or equipment.\nThe existing capacity was\nenough at the time to take\ncare of demand. Hence, the\nmoney poured into \u201cpump\npriming\u201d didn\u2019t have much\nvelocity or turnover. It didn\u2019t\nbring re-employment to the\nmillions in the bread lines\nfrom 1933 through 1939. The\nwar in 1940 really brought\nthe upward swing.\nFor it was only when the\nheavy-goods industries were\ngiven public works and arm\nament projects that fuller\nemployment came back. It\nwill do little good to the au\ntomobile workers of Detroit,\nso many of whom are out\nof work, if the \u201ctake home\u201d\npay of the other employes\nof the country is increased\nby only a couple of dollars\ncourage than subtlety. He\nleaked to newspapers the\ndamaging evidence he felt\nsubcommittee members\nwanted to suppress; he is now\ndemanding that, get a\npublic hearing on the.charges\nmade against him.\nAt one point the subcom\nmittee, though it is itself on\ntrial in the court of public\nopinion, threatened to fire\nMr. Schwartz after all. Then\nit belatedly realized that it\nwould be left under a cloud\nof suspicion that it wanted\nto cover up misdoing and\nvoted to retain him. Last\nnight it finally discharged\nhim.\nAll this incredible stupidity\nhas established a record of\nstill another kind. A small\ngroup of Senators who have\ntried vainly to get some\nsuch inquiry started in their\nchamber are poised to take\nthe issue to the Senate floor\nif the House subcommittee\ntries to sweep it under the\nrug.\nThe truth is that so much\nblood has now been drawn\nthe inquiry must go on. De\nspite the efforts of some\nsubcommittee members to\nhinder him, Mr. Schwartz\nhas managed to suggest\nthe status of basic, or funda\nmental. scientific research in\nvarious fields of nuclear and\nrelated science.\n7 Named to Map\nBoys Club Plan\nThe Metropolitan Police Boys\nClub, banned from using police\nofficers to solicit funds, last\nipight named a seven-man\ncommittee \u201cto iron things out\u201d\nwith the Commissioners.\nOmer W. Clark, president of\nthe club, said the committee\nincludes Fred Smith, Raymond\nF. Garrity, Morris Cafritz, Max\nFarrington, Edward Carr, Wash\nB. Williams and Tom Carney.\nThe group of prominent citi\nzens is expected to approach\nthe Commissioners, who issued\nthe ban, some time within the\nnext week.\nA week ago the club officers\nand past presidents drew up\na number of recommendations\nto solve the financial problems\nof the nine clubhouses. Tilts\ngroup last night turned the\nproblem over to the seven-man\ni special committee.\nboard was installed. One had\nto dial his Calls\u2014and look the\nnumber up in a book if he\ndidn't know it.\nBut someone felt \u201csome\nmembers of Congress might be\ntoo cantankerous to accept the\nI change with good grace,\u201d ac\ncording to Mr. Henderson. So\nthe dial phones and the man\n-1 ual phones were set side by side\non each member's desk.\nEven though he's had his\nsecond phone taken out (as\nI j have about a dozen other Con\ngressmen' he can still get the\noperator any time he wants her,\nMr. Henderson pointed out. All\nIhe has to do is dial \"O\u201d and;\n''she'll answer.\na week through tax reduc\ntion This could help buy\nmore food, but it would not\nhelp much to buy automo\nbiles even on the installment\nplan.\nIt is by adding substantial\nincreases to the employment\nrolls generally that industries\nlike steel and copper and\nother metals get the stimulus\nto recover. This can come\nwhen a general prosperity\nhas been achieved. Heavy\ngoods involves a multiplicity\nof transactions and, unlike\nconsumer Increases, they per\nmeate the whole economy.\nNaturally, the Democrats\nare having a field day talk\ning about how bad things are\nin business, while the Repub\nlicans keep saying things will\nbe better in the second six\nmonths of this year. Few ap\npraisals take into account the\npsychological effects of the\nslow-moving factors that are\nbehind the business recession.\nCertain bad situations must\nrun their course, and they\ntake time\u2014but when the\n\u201cpickup\u201d is delayed, some\nbusinessmen foolishly start\ncurtailing their own business\npurchases or deferring them.\nThis, in turn, puts a needless\nstrain on the whole situation.\nIf businessmen could op\nerate with a confidence that\ntheir products will be in good\ndemand again within 12\nmonths, they would be dis\nplaying real courage in the\nface of pessimistic forecasts.\nFor the truth is that, with a\nvast population growing\nlarger and larger each month\nand with America\u2019s plant and\ncapacity still less than is es\nsential to meet the require\nments of an expanding econ\nomy, the recovery is inevita\nble. The question of exactly\nwhat month will see the\n\u201cpickup\u201d is less important\nthan the fact that the \u201cpick\nup\u201d is certain.\n(Reproduction Rights Reserved)\nindelibly that very grave\ncorruption among the regu\nlatory agencies does exist.\nThe press is aroused and the\nissue is ready-made for all\npresent and potential an\ntagonists of the Congress\nmen involved.\nSome people already have\nbeen hurt, and more certainly\nwill be But there is no top\nsecret-security label available\nto pigeon-hole the matter.\nOs course, efforts will be\nmade to do so. Thqse who\nhave misused the agencies to\nwin economic benefits for\nthemselves will employ that\neconomic power to stop the\nunfolding of the story. Mem\nbers of Congress who allowed\nthemselves to be persuaded\nto exert pressure on the com\nmissions have no taste for\npublic hearings about it. The\ncommissioners, themselves, if\nthe first few witnesses are\nany test, do not enjoy the\nwitness stand. Some of them\nhave resisted the most rou\ntine inquiries about the con\nduct of their offices.\nPolitical secrets are hard to\nkeep, however, Vmd few poli\nticians care to face their con\nstituents in an election year\nwith the aura of one sur\nrounding them. How to get\nthe agency inquiry back on\nthe road and keep it there\nis the question before House\nleaders of both parties.\nSearchers Find\nWater Leakage\nJERSEY CITY, N. J., Feb. 11 i\nW\u2014The water main leak\ndraining this city's supply of\nwater at an alarming rate was\nlocated today and the state of,\nemergency was declared over.\n\u2018August W. Heckman, com\nmisisoner of public works, an\nnounced that the leak had been\npinpointed in a 36-inch main\nstarting at the city\u2019s small re\nceiving reservoir and running\nunder the Hackensack River.\nMuch Water Wasted\nThe leak, with millions of\ngallons of water going to waste,\nhad led to a state of emergency\nfor a third of this port city.\nHundreds of water works em\nployes had been searching for\nthe break since Sunday night\nwithout success.\nMost of the 40 control valves\nhad been closed one at a time\nin an effort to find the leak.\nThe possibility that the break\nmight result in cave-ins had\nbrought about the state of\nemergency.\nPressure Bull) tip\nAbout a third 4t the city's\n308,000 population was without\nwater for a while, until pressure\ncould be built up to offset\nthe leak.\nA total of 105 plants employ\ning 25.500 workers had been\nclosed in an effort to conserve\nwater and thus maintain pres\nsure. They made plans to\nreopen at noon today.\nTwenty schools were closed,\ngiving 16,000 pupils an un\nexpected holiday.\nThe pupils will return to\nschool Thursday, after a Lin\ncoln's Birthday holiday tomor\nrow.\nGarroways Have Boy\nNEW YORK. Feb. 11 </P).\ni A son was born Sunday to Mrs.\nDave Garroway, wife of the TV\nand radio performer. The baby,\ntheir first child, was named\nDavid Cqnnlngham Garroway\nafter his father. Mrs. Garroway\nwas Pamela Wilde, former\nactress and ballerina.\nLOUIE \u2014\u00bby Harry Hanan\ny j\nBo S I 381\nPOTOMAC FfVfO\nFLETCHER KNEBEL\n4 An opinion poll says Stevenson would beat Nixon for\npresident. One of those rousing elections where the winner\n*is the fellow who gets the least votes against.\n4**\nf Harry Truman will blast the Republicans at a 8100\nl Democratic dinner, February 22. Harry is expected to look\n1 the facts in the eye\u2014and call a spade a bull-dozer.\n\u25a0j\nA fellow is organizing the Lunar Protective Association.\n\u201cWhy throw things at the moon?\u201d he says. \"It never did\nanything to us.\u201d\n\nDr. Wernher von Braun, space rocketeer, was flattered\nwhen a teen-age girl asked him for two autographs. \u201cOh\nthanks,\" she said. \u201cNow I can trade two of yours for one of\nPresley's.\u201d\n\nThe Army\u2019s Gen. Gavin appears to be going on the theory\nthat the only way to get recognized in a uniform these days\nis to take it off.\nAilment May Prevent\nIves' Re-election Bid\nBy the Associated Press\nA mysterious ankle condition\nthat has ariseh to plague\nSenator Ives, Republidan of\nNew York, could mean he\nmight not seek re-election this\nyear.\nBenator Ives\u2019 son and admin\nistrative assistant, George S.\nIves, said if the condition re\nsists treatment the 62-year-old\nSenator will give serious con\nsideration to stepping out of\nthe Senate post to which he\nwas first elected in 1946.\nBut the younger Ives said the\nailment\u2014involving a swelling\nof the ankles\u2014is responding to\nmedication.\nThe swelling develops, the\nson said, when Senator Ives\nremains on his feet for any,\nconsiderable length of time. He.\nsaid doctors are unable to\nidentify the malady.\nm\nOnly on Broniff can you enjoy\u2014\n9#V Et- DORADO, DC-7C, the fastest, largest, most\nW j modem airliner to link the U.S.A. and South America,\nJT Deluxe first<lass \u2014no extra fore\u2014and excellent\nlow-cost tourist accommodations to\n\u00a7*l Jig //jjpfpl PANAMA LIMA SAO PAULO RIO\nfi JBk NEW EL CONQUISTADOR. Faster, finer, 4-engine\nmm* JmX 1 DC-6 flights between the U.S.A and 9 Latin American\ncountries Master-chef meals and Broniff\nfinest, most luxurious to\nboth first-class and MwJll NOWI Thr *'9 h\ntourist accommodations 1 I WA Rftftft TA\non all flights TWMM OWW I M\nI mmm Three deluxe NEW El Conquistodor flights weekly,\nAi\nLINKING THE AMERICAS\nof EA *T. E\nTallulah Bankhead\nEnters Hospital\nNEW YORK, Feb. 11 (/Pi.\u2014\nActress Tallulah Bankhead is\nin Lenox Hill Hospital with\nwhat she says is a \"possible\nkidney infection.\u201d Her con\ndition was reported good today.\nMiss Bankhead was taken by\nambulance to the hospital\nyesterday amid rumors that j\nshe had had soipe sort of i\nserious mishap. An anonymous 1\ncaller telephoned police to ask\nif she had been killed.\nThe 55-year-old actress later\ntalked to reporters by tele\nphone from her hospital room.\nShe said she wanted to end>\nrumors that She had been\nmurdered.\nShe also said she had been\ncoughing and feared a recur\nrence of pneumonia, from\nwhich she suffered last fall.\nCONSTANTINC BROWN\nU. S. Concern Over Tunisia Attack\nOfficials Fear We Will Be Blamed\nMore Than French for Air Raid\nWashington appears to be\nmore disturbed than Paris\nover the bombing of a Tuni\nsian village by 25 French\nbombers, 17 of which were\nmade in America and given\nto France under the NATO\nagreement.\nThe attack, which the\nFrench explained as their\nright of hot pursuit of hostile\nAlgerian nationalists, is like\nly to further consolidate the\nArab world behind Gamal\nAbdel Nasser, the president\nof the newly created United\nArab Republic.\nThe Arab Republic was a\nskillful Kremlin operation in\ntended to alienate completely\nthe Arabs the free West\nand to deprive Europe even\ntually of its most important\noil resources. It is true that\nPresident Nasser is not ideo\nlogically a Communist;\nneither does he tolerate the\nCommunist ideologies and\ntheir spokesmen in his realm.\nBut Moscow's policies are\nflexible. Comrade Khru\nshchev\u2019s main objective is the\n\u201cuniversality\u201d of the Soviet\nempire. The means to achieve\nthis is to bring America and\nits associates to their knees.\nHe can afford to abandon the\nMarxist-Leninist doctrines in\nan area where neither the\npeople nor, especially, the\nabsolute rulers want any part\nof it.\nThe activities of the Soviet\nUnion in the Arab world have\nbeen intended to develop na\ntionalism. In this, Russia has\nbeen highly successful. The\nArabs have responded enthu\nsiastically to the magic of\n\u201cnationalism.\u201d Furthermore,\nthey see for the first time in\nhistory that with the support\nof the USSR they can ac\ncomplish a long- awaited\ndream, \u201cpan-Islamism.\u201d This\nwould not only enable them\nto nationalize the vast oil\nwealth developed by Western\ncapital but also to get rid of\nIsrael without fear of repris\nals. The nationalization of\nthe oil fields and pipelines is\nexpected to give vast profits\nto the rulers. The destruc\ntion of Israel would delight\nthe Arab masses.\nThe progress of this gi\ngantic move has been strongly\nnoticeable in the region ex-\nDoOF LEA *O\nLA 6-6600\nGICHNER#\nTHE EVENING STAR, Washington, D. C.\nTtEBDAY, rgaacAav n, io&o\ntending from Egypt to Iraq.\nStrongly anti-Communist\ncountries such as Iraq and\nSaudi Arabia are now study\ning the new situation sympa\nthetically and are consider\ning the value of joining the\nUnited Arab Republic. Ques\ntions such as the sovereignty\nof the Kings of Iraq and\nSaudi Arabia are for the\ntune being in the way. But\nvarious plans to solve them\nare under consideration with\nthe aid of the Soviet \u201cexperts\u201d\nwho do not object to the\nanti-Communist sentiments of\nthe Arab rulers.\nThe area from Libya to\nMorocco has been less re\nsponsive to the Kremlin en\nticements. All the countries\nin that region obtained their\nfull sovereignty (except Al\ngeria. which is an integral\npart of Franci) with the as\nsistance of tie West. The\nkingdoms of Libya and Mo\nrocco and the Republic of\nTunisia are in the free world's\ncorner. The ruthless bom\nbardment of the Ti|nisian\nvillage on a market day when\nthe farmers from the sur\nrounding area came to the\nvillage may now change all\nthis. There were more than\n100 casualties, including wom\nen and children. The p>o-\nWestern Tunisian govern\nment is on the spot. The fact\nthat\" the matter may be\nbrought before the United\nNations Security Council will\nonly increase the tension.\nThe Soviet delegate is ex\npected to denounce loudly\nthe blood thirsty \"colonial\nists\u201d instead of trying to pour\noil on troubled waters. There\nis little we can do to counter\nthe propaganda which will\nensue from that unhappy\nincident.\nWhat the State Depart\nment fears most is that we\nshall be blamed more than\nthe French for what hap\npened at the village. The j\nSoviet Egyptian propaganda\nfor whom the death of these\n\nE Florida's Fabulous^\nPORT#^|\nARLOTTE\nadvertised in\nLOOK j\nCurrent Issue \u2019j\nnrt Are* uawWrV Lt\n\\131 399k\nFlorida Rooms op\u00abn 7 Days a Weak\n1613 EYE ST.. N.W. NA. 1-6440\n121 S.Wnlr. St Falls CH. IE. 3 1212\ninnocent Tunisians are a\nbonanza will point an accus\ning finger at Washington aa\nthe real culprit, since most\nof the light bombers which\nparticipated in the punitive\nraid were made in America.\nWe are already hearing on\nthe airwaves that the French\nwere only the \u201carm of the\nAmerican imperialists.\u201d\nThe Islamic world began\nto lose faith and respect for\nour principal European allies\n\u2014the French and British\u2014\nafter the end of World War\n11. The failure of the French\nand British military expedi\ntion against Nasser in Novem\nber, 1956, resulted in further\ncollapse of whatever prestige\nthese two countries still had\namong the Arabs. There is\nno need for those who want\nto make the Middle East into\na Soviet enclave to further\nharp on these two West Eu\nropean powers. America is\nthe target of the master\nminds in Moscow and Cairo.\nThe administration would\nlike to take a strong moral\nstand against our French\nally. This could offset the\nexploitation of the Tunisian\n.ncident against us. But the\nState Department is more\naware than is the public of\nthe weakness of NATO.\nPushing France too hard\nmight result in another min\nisterial crisis in Paris and\nmark the beginning of the\nend of the NATO pact. This\nthe administration can af\nford just as little as antago\nnizing the Islamic world.\nI a\nJust one bottle\np\nmakes any drinkl\nP\nSamovar\nVODKA\n\u2022lit. from piln. SO ontf 100 Proof.\nSchtnloy Dill Co., N.V.C.\na\nA-13","height":"28556","width":"17977"}}
